WEBVTT

NOTE Captions for "Identity keys, safety numbers, and TOFU pinning" (Topic 6). No
NOTE audio track yet by decision; these captions carry the narration. Source of
NOTE truth: learn/manim/scripts/identity-keys.md

00:00.000 --> 00:15.000
Encryption protects the message. It doesn't tell you who's on the other end. When you first message someone, your app asks our servers for their public key. And that's the gap.

00:15.000 --> 00:35.000
Watch. Alice asks for Bob's key. We hand her one labelled "Bob" — but it's ours. Now everything Alice sends opens here, gets read, and gets re-sealed for Bob. Look at their screens. Padlocks. Both of them. Nothing looks wrong, because nothing is wrong with the encryption. It's working perfectly — on the wrong key.

00:35.000 --> 00:55.000
Every end-to-end encrypted app has this problem. Here are the two answers. First: safety numbers. Your device combines your identity key with your contact's and produces a short code. They do the same. Same two keys, same code — it matches.

00:55.000 --> 01:10.000
Now run the attack again. Alice's device is mixing in our key, not Bob's. Different inputs, different codes. Compare them any way we can't interfere with — hold the phones together, read them out on a call, scan the QR — and the middleman is caught immediately.

01:10.000 --> 01:30.000
The catch is obvious. It only works if you actually check. And most people never do. So there's a second answer, and it works even when nobody checks.

01:30.000 --> 01:55.000
Every identity key we publish goes into a public log that only ever grows. To pull off that attack, we'd have to publish the fake key — here, in the open, permanently. And watch us try to take it back. We can't. The log doesn't work that way.

01:55.000 --> 02:15.000
And your own device is reading that log. It compares what the world is being shown for you against the key you actually hold. If they ever disagree, your app tells you. The attack stops being invisible and becomes permanent public proof that we cheated.

02:15.000 --> 02:35.000
One last thing. The first time you talk to someone, your app remembers their key. If it ever changes, you get a banner. Usually that's innocent — a new phone, a reinstall. Sometimes it isn't. Your app can't tell the difference, which is why it asks you.

02:35.000 --> 02:45.000
Compare safety numbers once, with the people who matter. The log handles the rest.
